# No Contract Data Patching in Tests

## Rule

**Never, under any circumstances, patch raw contract data structures in tests.** Use real emitted fixtures. If a test really has to generate a contract at runtime, it may only generate it from a high-level representation made with a user-facing authoring surface (contract builder DSL, PSL) — never by writing, or worse, patching, the raw contract data structure.

## Why

Patched contracts drift from anything the emitter can produce: they skip authoring-time validation, encode shapes no user can reach, and silently keep passing when the real contract format changes. Tests then assert behavior for contracts that cannot exist.

## Don't

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: spreading/overriding raw contract internals
const contract = withPatchedDomainModels(getTestContract(), (models) => ({
  ...models,
  Project: {
    ...project,
    relations: {
      ...project.relations,
      related: { ...related, through: { ...related.through, targetColumns: ['tenant_id'] } },
    },
  },
}));
```

## Do

```typescript
// ✅ Use the real emitted fixture (test/fixtures/generated/contract.json + contract.d.ts)
const contract = getTestContract();

// ✅ Or generate at runtime from a user-facing authoring surface
const contract = defineContract({ models: { User, Post } });

// ✅ If the scenario cannot be authored (e.g. malformed metadata rejected at
// authoring time), test the defensive guard directly with its own typed inputs
expect(() =>
  buildPairedColumnExprs('project_links', ['dst_tenant_id', 'dst_id'], 'projects', ['tenant_id']),
).toThrow(/mismatched join column counts/);
```

## Notes

- Capability overrides via a dedicated typed helper (e.g. `withCapabilities`) that swaps a whole well-typed top-level slot are acceptable; reaching into domain models, storage entries, or relation metadata is not.
- When an existing test relies on a patched contract, migrate it to an emitted fixture or a direct unit test of the code the patch was trying to reach.

